'''Kasami Shrine'' (Kasami Shrine) is {{ill|lt=Shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|qid=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City|Q641491|qid=Q641491|1=Kakamigahara}}{{ill|lt=Sohara Old Market Town|Q131870109|qid=Q131870109|1=Sohara Old Market Town}}. Located on the left bank of {{ill|lt=Shinsakaigawa|Q11501642|qid=Q11501642|1=Shinsakai River}}, east-southeast of Mt. Kasami.{{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|qid=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchisha|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}. Originally 10 villages of Sohara ({{ill|lt=Ibishima Village|Q18990514|qid=Q18990514|lt=Ibuki, Asuka, Shimazaki|1=Ibijima}}, {{ill|lt=Wago Village (Inaba District, Gifu Prefecture)|Q23940976|qid=Q23940976|lt=Noguchi, Kumada, Higashijima, Sakai|1=Wagō}}, {{ill|lt=Omiya Village (Gifu Prefecture)|Q18748127|qid=Q18748127|lt=Oshima/Miyashiro|1=Ōmiya}}・{{ill|lt=Furuichi Market Village (Kakamami District, Gifu Prefecture)|Q22125133|qid=Q22125133|lt=Furuichi Market|1=Furuichiba}}) is {{ill|lt=Soja|Q1107129|qid=Q1107129|1=Sōja shrine}}, but it is currently considered to be the Sojajin of {{ill|lt=Sohara Town|Q11625179|qid=Q11625179|lt=Sohara District|1=Sohara}} and {{ill|lt=Udojin|Q1392097|qid=Q1392097|1=Ubusunagami}}. {{ill|lt=Modern company rank system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=Old company rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is a Gosha.

It is one of the {{ill|lt=Kinpeisha|Q119929592|qid=Q119929592|1=Kinpei-sha}} five shrines in Kakamigahara City, <ref>[https://www.tezikarao.org/news/detail.php?id=149 Kakamigahara City Kinpei Five Shrines Tour], Gifu Prefectural Shrine Agency Kakamigahara City Branch</ref>.

=== Summary ==={{ill|lt=864|Q25041|qid=Q25041|1=864}} ({{ill|lt=Jokan (Japan)|Q1075635|qid=Q1075635|lt=Jokan|1=Jōgan}}6), founded by {{ill|lt=Emperor Seiwa|Q349243|qid=Q349243|1=Emperor Seiwa}}. In the past, this area was ruled by {{ill|lt=Soga clan|Q909854|qid=Q909854|1=Soga clan}} such as {{ill|lt=Sogakura Yamada Ishikawamaro|Q3488899|qid=Q3488899|1=Soga no Kurayamada no Ishikawa no Maro}}, and the place name ``Sohara'' is said to have come from the Soga clan's possession. It is said that after Sogakura Yamada Ishikawamaro passed away, the people of Sohara Manor (currently Sohara) worshiped him and held rituals there, and the shrine itself may have existed in the {{ill|lt=7th century|Q8089|qid=Q8089|1=7th century}}. It is said that around {{ill|lt=905|Q24239|qid=Q24239|1=905}} ({{ill|lt=Enki|Q1374325|qid=Q1374325|1=Engi (era)}}5), it was located in {{ill|lt=Kakamami District|Q11412369|qid=Q11412369|1=Kakami district}} Soharasho Old Market and was called Hachiman Shrine. It is said that it was called Kasami Myojin in {{ill|lt=908|Q30463|qid=Q30463|1=908}} (Engi 8). Furthermore, according to the middle volume of "{{ill|lt=Prefectural Gosha Meiji Shrine Journals|Q11486103|qid=Q11486103|lt=Fugata Gosha Meiji Shrine Journals|1=Fuken Gōsha Meiji Jinja Shiryō}}" published {{ill|lt=1912|Q2077|qid=Q2077|1=1912}} (Meiji 45), the {{ill|lt=enshrined deity|Q11591100|qid=Q11591100|1=Saijin}} and the year of its founding are unknown<ref>{{Cite journal |Japanese book |title=Gifu Prefecture |journal={{ill|lt=Prefecture Gosha Meiji Shrine Magazine|Q11486103|qid=Q11486103|lt=Prefectural Gosha Meiji Shrine Magazine|1=Fuken Gōsha Meiji Jinja Shiryō}} |volume=Volume 2 |publisher=Meiji Shrine Magazine |date=1912-01-15 |pages=36-37 |doi=10.11501/1088278}}</ref>.In "{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}" {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, there is "Kasami Shrine" in the seven temples of Kagami District in {{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|qid=Q864156|lt=Minokuni|1=Mino Province}} Kaminashita |journal={{ill|lt=Kokushi Taikei|Q10926780|qid=Q10926780|lt=Kokushi Taikei|1=Kokushi Taikei}} |volume=13 |publisher={{ill|lt=Keizai Zasshisha|Q11606486|qid=Q11606486|1=Keizai Zasshisha}} |date=1900-11-15 |pages=346 |doi=10.11501/991103}}</ref>, "Minokuni Shinmecho" lists "{{ill|lt=Senior Fourth Rank|Q11123338|qid=Q11123338|lt=Senior Fourth Rank Lower|1=Senior Fourth Rank}}Kasamita Myojin" among the 23 shrines in Kagami-gunza<ref>{{Cite journal |Japanese book |editor={{ill|lt=Yiyoshi Saeki|Q11382847|qid=Q11382847|1=Saeki Ariyoshi}} etc. |title=Enryakuji Hon Mino Province Shinmecho |journal=Jingi Zensho |volume=Volume 4 |publisher={{ill|lt=Koten Kokyujo|Q11580997|qid=Q11580997|1=Koten Kokyusho}} |date=1908-05-17 |pages=624 |doi=10.11501/991328}}</ref><ref name="Kakamigahara City History">{{Cite journal |Japanese book |editor=Kakamigahara City Board of Education |title=Section 2 Shrines as seen in the Engishiki Shinmyocho |journal=Kakamigahara City History |volume=General history Nature, primitive, ancient, medieval |publisher=Kakamigahara City |date=1986-12-20 |pages=626-630 |doi=10.11501/9571788}}</ref>. In addition, in the "Kakamigahara City History", "{{ill|lt=Japan Three Dynasties Annals|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}" August 15, 864 {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Kimi|1=UNKNOWN}}Article ``{{ill|lt=Mino Province|Q864156|qid=Q864156|1=Mino Province}}{{ill|lt=Junior Fifth Rank|Q11071125|qid=Q11071125|lt=Junior Fifth Rank Lower|1=Junior Fifth Rank}}Kasami Kamishō<small>ku </small><sub>Two</sub>Junior Fifth Rank Upper<small>wo</small><sub>One</sub>'', but at the time of {{Efn|{{ill|lt=quote|Q206287|qid=Q206287|1=Quotation}}, {{ill|lt=Chinese numerals|Q683566|qid=Q683566|1=Chinese numerals}} was changed to {{ill|lt=Arabic numerals|Q29961325|qid=Q29961325|1=Arabic numerals}}. }}<ref name="Kakamigahara City History"/>, the description varies depending on the manuscript. In the ``Nihon Sandai Jiroku'' published in {{ill|lt=1914|Q2083|qid=Q2083|1=1914}} ({{ill|lt=Taisho|Q329174|qid=Q329174|1=Taishō era}}3), which is based on ``Mino Province'', <ref>{{Cite journal |Japanese book |title=Third Dynasty Actual Record Volume 9 Emperor Seiwa (August 6th year of Teikō) |journal=Japan's Third Dynasty Actual Record |publisher=Keizai Zasshisha |date=1914-02-28 |pages=184 |quote=15th Kimimi. Mino Province Junior Fifth Rank Shimonagata no Kami. Mengami Kanda God. Kasamikami. (omitted) Parallel class<sub>2</sub>Junior Fifth Rank Upper<sub>1</sub> {{j alink|1944|Q5268}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 19th year) "Japan Three Generations Jitsuroku" says "{{ill|lt=Mimasakakuni|Q936036|qid=Q936036|1=Mimasaka Province}}"<ref>{{Cite journal |Japanese book |title=Third Dynasty Actual Record Volume 9 Emperor Seiwa (August 1987) |journal=Japan's Three Dynasty Actual Record |publisher=Daiyashu Publishing Founding Office |date=1944-06-28 |pages=140 |quote=15th Kimi. Mimasakakuni Jugoi Shimonagata no Kami. Mengami Kanda God. Former shrine deity. (omitted) Parallel class <sub>2</sub>Junior Fifth Rank Upper <sub>1</sub> |doi=10.11501/3456452}}</ref>. }}.In the precincts there are {{ill|lt=Amida-do|Q11657414|qid=Q11657414|1=Amida-dō}} and {{ill|lt=Yakushi-do|Q11622438|qid=Q11622438|1=Bhaiṣajyaguru Hall}}, and there are remnants of {{ill|lt=Shinto-Buddhist syncretism|Q2279088|qid=Q2279088|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō}}. Nemotoji once existed as {{ill|lt=Jinguji|Q1074971|qid=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}}, but in the early Meiji period, it became {{ill|lt=Abandoned Temple|Q11486287|qid=Q11486287|1=former Buddhist temple}} in {{ill|lt=Haibutsu Kishaku|Q702298|qid=Q702298|1=Haibutsu kishaku}}. The main shrine (built in {{ill|lt=1687|Q7668|qid=Q7668|1=1687}}), the shrine (built in {{ill|lt=1910|Q2075|qid=Q2075|1=1910}}), and the worship hall (built in {{ill|lt=1746|Q7589|qid=Q7589|1=1746}}) are |2008|Q1069941}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}}20) Registered as a national {{ill|lt=registered tangible cultural property|Q11579194|qid=Q11579194|1=Registered Tangible Cultural Property of Japan}} on April 18th <ref>{{Cite web |Japanese book |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami3.html |title=Kasami Shrine Main Hall |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-20 |archiveurl=https://warp.da.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2611608/www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami3.html |archivedate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cultural Heritage Online|144291|Kasami Shrine Main Hall}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |Japanese books |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami2.html |title=Kasami Shrine Heiden |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-20 |archiveurl=https://warp.da.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2611608/www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami2.html |archivedate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cultural Heritage Online|172332|Kasami Shrine Heideden}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |Japanese books |url=http://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami1.html |title=Kasami Shrine Hall of Worship |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2013-04-20 |archiveurl=https://warp.da.ndl.go.jp/info:ndljp/pid/2611608/www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/kyoiku-bunka-sports/bunka-geijutsu/bunkazai-zuroku/bunkazai-zuroku/touyuubun/kagamiharsi/kasami1.html |archivedate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cultural Heritage Online|186933|Kasami Shrine Worship Hall}}</ref><ref name="Kasami Shrine">``Shikiuchi Kinpeisha Kasami Shrine Bookmark''</ref>.It has a deep connection with the Soga clan, and in the surrounding area there are the tomb of Soga Ishikawamaro ({{ill|lt=legendary Sogakura Yamada Ishikawamaro's tomb|Q11381424|qid=Q11381424|1=legendary Sogakura Yamada Ishikawamaro's tomb}}) and the ruins of Yamada-dera Temple ({{ill|lt=Yamada-dera Pagoda Heart Foundation|Q11470319|qid=Q11470319|1=Yamada-dera Pagoda Heart Foundation}}).

{{ill|lt=1975|Q2479|qid=Q2479|1=1975}} ({{ill|lt=Showa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}}50th year) On September 16th, it was designated as Kinpeisha by Gifu Prefecture Shinto President Designation No. 76<ref name="Kasami Shrine"/><ref>{{Cite web |Japanese book |url=https://www.gifu-jinjacho.jp/syosai.php?shrno=780 |title=Kasami Shrine |publisher=Gifu Prefectural Shrine Agency |accessdate=2025-05-09}}</ref>.{{ill|lt=Sando|Q667783|qid=Q667783|1=Sandō}} corresponds to a part of {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City#City Road Common Name|Q641491|qid=Q641491|lt=Sohara Chuo-dori|1=Kakamigahara}}, and {{ill|lt=Otabisho|Q11489117|qid=Q11489117|1=Otabisho}} is located along the approach to Sohara Furuichiba-cho 2-chome. In the past, there were two torii gates and three torii gates on the approach to the shrine, and the latter gate was connected to Sowara Chuo Dori and {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City#Common names of roads in the city|Q641491|qid=Q641491|lt=Ogase Kaido|1=Kakamigahara}}. The intersection, Sannotorii, is said to have existed at the intersection of Sowara Chuo-dori Street and {{ill|lt=Kakamigahara City#Common name for roads in the city|Q641491|qid=Q641491|lt=Yamada-dera Street|1=Kakamigahara}}<ref name="Key Scenic Area">{{Cite book |Japanese book |url=https://www.city.kakamigahara.lg.jp/_res/projects/default_project/_page_/001/008/305/03_kasami240815.pdf |title=Kakamigahara City District Landscape Plan Landscape Formation Standards Guidelines Key Scenic District 3 Kasami Shrine District |format=PDF |publisher=Kakamigahara City |page=1 |accessdate=2025-02-26}}</ref>.Kasami Shrine once had Ichinomiya, Ninomiya, and Sannomiya, and Ichinomiya was the Shinmei Shrine in Furuichiba Village, Kagami District (now Sohara Furuichiba Town). (Kakamigahara City, Sohara Furuichiba Town)|Q134987025|Shinmei Shrine}}, Ninomiya is {{jalink|Yasaka Shrine} in Ibuki Village, Kakamiga District (currently {{ill|lt=Sohara Ibuki Town|Q131900799|qid=Q131900799|1=Sohara Ibuki Town}}) (Sohara Ibuki-cho, Kakamigahara City)|Q134928112|Yasaka Shrine}}, Sannomiya is Kumano Shrine {{Efn|{{ill|lt=1909|Q2057|qid=Q2057|1=1909}} (Meiji 42), {{ill|lt=Shinmei Shrine (Sohara Noguchi Town, Kakamigahara City)|Q134926762|qid=Q134926762|lt=Shinmei Shrine|1=Shinmei Shrine (Noguchi-chō, Sohara, Kakamigahara)}} ({{ill|lt=Sohara Noguchi Town|Q131870111|qid=Q131870111|1=Sohara Noguchi Town}}). }}<ref name="base stone">From the local commentary board ``Kasami Shrine "Nino Torii" base stone''</ref>. Based on the Kakamigahara City {{ill|lt=Landscape Ordinance|Q11514689|qid=Q11514689|lt=Urban Landscape Ordinance|1=Regulations of cityscape (in Japan)}}, on August 1, 2008|Q2004, Kakamigahara City Notification No. 80 designated approximately 37.29{{ill|lt=ha|Q35852|qid=Q35852|1=Hectare}} surrounding the shrine as a key scenic area.<ref>{{Cite web |Japanese book |url=https://www.city.kakamigahara.lg.jp/shisei/shisaku/1008207/1008297/1008302/1008305.html |title=Important scenic areas (determined) Districts with historical resources and scenery |publisher=Kakamigahara City |date=2024-08-16 |accessdate=2025-05-09}}</ref>.During the {{ill|lt=Sengoku period (Japan)|Q204023|qid=Q204023|lt=Sengoku period|1=Sengoku period}}, Kasami Shrine was called {{ill|lt=Hachimangu|Q11390939|qid=Q11390939|1=Hachiman shrine}}, and Mt. Kasami on the mountain behind the shrine was also called Mt. Hachiman, and {{ill|lt=Hachimanyama Castle (Mino Province)|Q38276751|qid=Q38276751|lt=Hachimanyama Castle|1=Hachimanyama Castle}}<ref name="Important Scenic Area"/>

=== Enshrined God ===
* Kasami Okami
** According to one theory, ``Kasamiyama'' itself, located to the west-northwest of Kasami Shrine, was once an object of worship. It is assumed that Kasami Okami considered Mt. Kasami as a god.
* {{ill|lt=Sogakura Yamada Ishikawamaro|Q3488899|qid=Q3488899|1=Soga no Kurayamada no Ishikawa no Maro}}
* {{ill|lt=Emperor Ojin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|1=Emperor Ōjin}}

=== Precinct Company ===
* Akiba Shrine ({{ill|lt=Kagutsuchi|Q1640658|qid=Q1640658|lt=Katsuchijin|1=Kagu-tsuchi}}) <ref name="Kasami Shrine"/>
* Okuwa Shrine ({{ill|lt=Toyoukebime|Q2983724|qid=Q2983724|lt=Toyouke Okami|1=Toyouke-hime}}) <ref name="Kasami Shrine"/>
* Kasami Inari Shrine ({{ill|qid=Q3080728|lt=Ukanomitama|Q3080728|qid=Q3080728|lt=Kuraina Tama no Mikoto|1=Ukanomitama}}) <ref name="Kasami Shrine"/>
